{{italic title}} The '''''Ainu Times''''' is the only [[magazine]] published in the [[Ainu language]]. Its first edition was published for 20 March 1997.<ref name="SynakWicherkiewicz1997">{{cite book|author1=Brunon Synak|author2=Tomasz Wicherkiewicz|title=Language minorities and minority languages in the changing Europe: proceedings of the 6th International Conference on Minority Languages, Gdańsk, 1-5 July, 1996|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_FRiAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=9 June 2012|year=1997|publisher=Wydawn. Uniwersytetu Gdańskiego|isbn=978-83-7017-772-0}}</ref> It uses both special [[katakana]] and [[romanization]]s in its articles. Its editor as of 2006 is guitarist [[Takashi Hamada]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://sologuitar.jp/takashi-hamada/|title=浜田隆史 {{!}} SOLO GUITAR RECORDS|date=2015-03-16|work=SOLO GUITAR RECORDS|access-date=2017-11-22|language=ja}}</ref> It is published four times a year. A Japanese version of each issue, containing Japanese translations of the issue's contents, is published three months after the issue's initial publication.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.geocities.jp/otarunay/taimuzu.html#times|title=アイヌタイムズ|website=www.geocities.jp|access-date=2017-11-22}}</ref>
==External links== * [http://www.geocities.jp/otarunay/taimuzu.html ''Ainu Times'' homepage (by Takasi Hamada, in Ainu and Japanese)] ([https://www.webcitation.org/5kmDfSRm5 Archived] 2009-10-24) * [http://www.geocities.jp/otarunay/index.html オタルナイ・レコード] ([https://www.webcitation.org/5kmDer5HU Archived] 2009-10-24) (includes pages on Ainu Times) * [http://www.geocities.co.jp/aynuitak/kana_utf-8/AT33_ain_jp_eo_utf8.htm cakcak kamuy oruspe] (example of Ainu Times, in Ainu, Japanese and Esperanto, by YOKOYAMA Hiroyuki, a member of [http://www.hokkajda-esp-ligo.jp/ind_en.htm Hokkaido Esperanto League (HEL)] in JAPAN)
