{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}} The [[BBC]] broadcasts all of the [[BBC One]] and [[BBC Two]] regional variations on digital satellite television from the [[SES S.A.|SES]] [[Astra (satellites)|Astra]] satellites at [[Astra 28.2°E|28.2° east]];<ref name="freetoair"> {{cite press release | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2003/03_march/12/digital_sat.shtml | title = BBC goes in the clear on digital satellite | date = 12 March 2003 | accessdate = 23 March 2010 | publisher = BBC | quote = The BBC today (Wednesday 12 March 2003) announced that from 30 May it will, for the first time, broadcast its eight TV channels unencrypted on digital satellite. The BBC national services in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, plus, for the first time, all 15 regional variations of BBC ONE in England will all be available on DSAT. It also means that the BBC will save an estimated £85&nbsp;million over the next five years because it will no longer be using BSkyB's Conditional Access system. }} </ref> providing local news programmes and other regional programming with local [[Continuity (broadcasting)|continuity]] and presentation for Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales. The BBC refers to the whole UK regional network as "BBC Nations and Regions".<ref name="nations-regions"> {{cite web | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/keyfacts/stories/nationsregions.shtml | publisher = BBC | title= Key Facts, BBC Nations and Regions | work = BBC Press Office | date = August 2004 | accessdate = 29 August 2007 }} </ref>
The local version of BBC One is normally on channel 101, with BBC Two on channel 102. On [[Freesat]] equipment, users enter a postcode during initial set up—this determines the correct local version. On [[Sky Digital (UK & Ireland)|Sky]] equipment, the address to which the viewing card was issued determines the correct local version—without any viewing card the London versions are shown by default.<ref name="skychan"> {{cite web | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/reception/info/channels_sky.shtml | publisher = BBC | work = Help Receiving BBC TV and Radio | title = BBC channel numbers on Sky | accessdate = 23 March 2010 }} </ref> All other national and regional versions are shown in the [[Electronic program guide|EPG]].
==History== From the launch of digital satellite on 1 October 1998 until 31 March 2001, there were four variants (England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland) of both [[BBC One]] and [[BBC Choice]] carried on all digital platforms. Only one version of [[BBC Two]] was available digitally, and this was shown throughout the UK. The [[BBC English Regions]] gradually became available via [[Digital Terrestrial Television]] ([[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]]) over the next few years, as did the national versions of BBC Two.
On digital satellite television, regional news programmes on BBC One were replaced by ''[[UK Today]]'' until 28 January 2002 when additional transponder space was allocated the English regions. Initially programmes were available as an [[Interactive television|interactive service]] via the [[BBC Red Button|red button]] and only for the five largest English regions; [[BBC London|London]], [[BBC North West|North West]], [[BBC South|South]], [[BBC West Midlands|West Midlands]] and [[BBC Yorkshire|Yorkshire]]<ref> {{cite press release | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2002/01_january/10/satellitenews.shtml | title = English Regions launch first phase of digital satellite news service | publisher = BBC | date = 10 January 2002 | accessdate = 22 March 2010 }} </ref> On 30 May 2003 the BBC stopped encrypting its TV channels on digital satellite and made all regions available as standard, full-time channels.<ref name="freetoair" />
==BBC regional services and channel numbers==
{{see|List of BBC regional news programmes}}
===BBC One=== Regional news inserts are broadcast during ''[[BBC Breakfast]]'' along with 15-minute shows on weekdays after [[BBC News|national news]] bulletins at 1.30&nbsp;pm and 10.30&nbsp;pm, along with a 30-minute show at 6.30&nbsp;pm. On weekends the availability of a regional news bulletin following the national news depends on the timeslot.
In England—other than regional news programmes—regional opt-outs include the documentary strand ''[[Inside Out (2002 TV programme)|Inside Out]]'', a regional segment of ''[[Sunday Politics]]'' and in the northern regions (those based in Hull, Leeds, Manchester and Newcastle) ''[[Super League Show|The Super League Show]]''.
Elsewhere, additional local programming is broadcast; (notable examples include ''[[Give My Head Peace]]'' and ''[[Spotlight (BBC Northern Ireland TV programme)|Spotlight]]'' in Northern Ireland, ''[[River City]]'' and ''[[Sportscene]]'' in Scotland and ''[[Belonging (TV series)|Belonging]]'' and ''[[Crash (2009 TV series)|Crash]]'' in Wales) with network programmes rescheduled to accommodate them.
BBC One HD started broadcasting on 3 November 2010. There are currently four regional variations – a network variant for England, a Northern Ireland variant that launched on 24 October 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/reception/info/sat_frequencies.shtml|title=BBC - Help receiving TV and radio - Satellite frequencies of BBC channels|accessdate=20 October 2010}}</ref> a Scottish variation that launched on 14 January 2013 and a Welsh variation that launched on 29 January 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/aboutthebbc/posts/Launching-BBC-One-Scotland-HD-and-BBC-One-Wales-HD|title=Launching BBC One Scotland HD and BBC One Wales HD|publisher=BBC|date=11 January 2013}}</ref>
